<h3>Servant Leadership</h3>

<p>
<i >&#8220;“Be ye followers of me, even as I also am of Christ.” 1 Corinthians 11:1 (KJV)&#8221;</i><br />
<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Perhaps the strongest tenet of our philosophy is our commitment to consciously bringing faith into the daily action and lives of our students. Intentional discipleship means that we explore the meaning of discipleship and create an environment to help our students grow in Christ and live as disciples, loving God, their friends, and family members as themselves.  As disciples of Jesus, we are all on a continuing journey of being transformed by the Holy Spirit into Christ’s likeness, experiencing and expressing love for God and others.  We facilitate this through daily actions and programs such as:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong><em>Open Bible Study  </em></strong>All high school students are invited to “open” bible studies to interact with Mr. and Mrs. D and receive a challenge from the Word of God.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong><em>Tea Parties and Muggings </em></strong>Sixteenth birthdays are celebrated in this cultural evening event, with young women receiving a tea cup and young men a mug along with blessings and a Biblical challenge from their friends and family members.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong><em>The Servant Leader Program </em></strong>We are unique in our hands-on teaching approach which is facilitated in part through our Servant Leadership Program.  We embrace intentional discipleship that fully develops the young person and prepares them to glorify God in this world and the next.  We encourage all students to participate in our Servant leader program.  All Apprentice Servant Leaders and Service Leaders are expected to assist a teacher in at least one class. By teaching others, they take their own learning to a whole new level. In the end, many of the younger students find themselves emulating and desiring to be like the Servant Leaders.  A legacy of stewardship is thus developed at a young age with our students.</p>



